Chapter Eleven

Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter


11.1  Introduction
The Maxwell’s equations of electromagnetism and Hertz experiments on the generation and detection of electromagnetic waves in 1887 strongly established the wave nature of light.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "Towards the same period at the end of 19th century, experimental investigations on conduction of electricity (electric discharge) through gases at low pressure in a discharge tube led to many historic discoveries.", "fibs": ["period"]}
{"text": "The discovery of X-rays by Roentgen in 1895, and of electron by J. J. Thomson in 1897, were important milestones in the understanding of atomic structure.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "It was found that at sufficiently low pressure of about 0.001 mm of mercury column, a discharge took place between the two electrodes on applying the electric field to the gas in the discharge tube.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "A fluorescent glow appeared on the glass opposite to cathode.", "fibs": ["glow"]}
{"text": "The colour of glow of the glass depended on the type of glass, it  being  yellowish-green for soda glass.", "fibs": ["colour"]}
{"text": "The cause of this fluorescence was attributed to the radiation which appeared to be coming from the cathode.", "fibs": ["cause"]}
{"text": "These cathode rays were discovered, in 1870, by William Crookes who later, in 1879, suggested that these rays consisted of streams of fast moving negatively charged particles.", "fibs": ["cathode"]}
{"text": "The British physicist J. J. Thomson (1856-1940) confirmed this hypothesis.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "By applying mutually perpendicular electric and magnetic fields across the discharge tube, J. J. Thomson was the first to determine experimentally the speed and the specific charge [charge to mass ratio (e/m)] of the cathode ray particles.", "fibs": ["discharge"]}
{"text": "They were found to travel with speeds ranging from about 0.1 to 0.2 times the speed of light (3 ×108 m/s).", "fibs": ["travel"]}
{"text": "The presently accepted value of e/m is 1.76 × 10­11 C/kg.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "Further, the value of e/m was found to be independent of the nature of the material/metal used as the cathode (emitter), or the gas introduced in the discharge tube.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "This observation suggested the universality of the cathode ray particles.", "fibs": ["observation"]}
{"text": "Around the same time, in 1887, it was found that certain metals, when irradiated by ultraviolet light, emitted negatively charged particles having small speeds.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "Also, certain metals when heated to a high temperature were found to emit negatively charged particles.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "The value of e/m of these particles was found to be the same as that for cathode ray particles.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "These observations thus established that all these particles, although produced under different conditions, were identical in nature.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "J. J. Thomson, in 1897, named these particles as electrons, and suggested that they were fundamental, universal  constituents of matter.", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "For his epoch-making discovery of electron, through his theoretical and experimental investigations on conduction of electricity by gasses, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1906.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "In 1913, the American physicist R. A. Millikan (1868-1953) performed the pioneering oil-drop experiment for the precise measurement of the charge on an electron.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "He found that  the charge on an oil-droplet was always an integral multiple of an elementary charge, 1.602 × 10–19 C. Millikan’s experiment established that electric charge is quantised.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "From the values of charge (e) and specific charge (e/m), the mass (m) of the electron could be determined.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "11.2  Electron Emission
We know that metals have free electrons (negatively charged particles) that are responsible for their conductivity.", "fibs": ["Emission"]}
{"text": "However, the free electrons cannot normally escape out of the metal surface.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "If an electron attempts to come out of the metal, the metal surface acquires a positive charge  and pulls the electron back to  the metal.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "The free electron is thus held inside the metal surface by the attractive forces of the ions.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Consequently, the electron can come out of the metal surface only if it has got sufficient energy to overcome the attractive pull.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "A certain minimum amount of energy is required to be given  to an electron to pull it out from the surface of the metal.", "fibs": ["amount"]}
{"text": "This minimum energy required by an electron to escape from the metal surface is called the work function of the metal.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "It is generally denoted by φ0 and measured in ev (electron volt).", "fibs": ["φ0"]}
{"text": "One electron volt is the energy gained by an electron when it has been accelerated by  a  potential difference  of 1 volt, so that  1 eV = 1.602 ×10–19 J.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "This unit of energy is commonly used in atomic and nuclear physics.", "fibs": ["unit"]}
{"text": "The work function (φ0)  depends on the properties of the metal and the nature of its surface.", "fibs": ["work"]}
{"text": "The values of work function of some metals are given in Table 11.1.", "fibs": ["work"]}
{"text": "These values are approximate as they are very sensitive to surface impurities.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Note from Table 11.1 that the work function of platinum is the highest (φ0 = 5.65 eV) while it is the lowest (φ0 = 2.14 eV) for caesium.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "The minimum energy required for the electron emission from the metal surface can be supplied to the free electrons by any one of the following physical processes:





(i)	Thermionic emission: By suitably heating, sufficient thermal energy can be imparted to the free electrons to enable them to come out of the metal.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "(ii)	Field emission: By applying a very strong electric field (of the order of 108 V m–1) to a metal, electrons can be pulled out of the metal, as in a spark plug.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii)	Photoelectric emission: When light of suitable frequency illuminates a metal surface, electrons are emitted from the metal surface.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "11.3  Photoelectric Effect
11.3.1  Hertz’s observations
The phenomenon of photoelectric emission was discovered in 1887 by Heinrich Hertz (1857-1894), during his electromagnetic wave experiments.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "In his experimental investigation on the production of electromagnetic waves by means of a spark discharge, Hertz observed that high voltage sparks across the detector loop were enhanced when the emitter plate was illuminated by ultraviolet light from an arc lamp.", "fibs": ["investigation"]}
{"text": "Light shining on the metal surface somehow facilitated the escape of free, charged particles which we now know as electrons.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "When light falls on a metal surface, some electrons near the surface absorb enough energy from the incident radiation to overcome the attraction of the positive ions in the material of the surface.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "After gaining sufficient energy from the incident light, the electrons escape from the surface of the metal into the surrounding space.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "11.3.2  Hallwachs’ and Lenard’s observations
Wilhelm Hallwachs and Philipp Lenard investigated the phenomenon of photoelectric emission in detail during 1886-1902.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Lenard (1862-1947) observed that when ultraviolet radiations were allowed to fall on the emitter plate of an evacuated glass tube enclosing two electrodes (metal plates), current flows in the circuit (Fig.", "fibs": ["fall"]}
{"text": "As soon as the ultraviolet radiations were stopped, the current flow also stopped.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "These observations indicate that when ultraviolet radiations fall on the emitter plate C, electrons are ejected from it which are attracted towards the positive, collector plate A by the electric field.", "fibs": ["fall"]}
{"text": "The electrons flow through the evacuated glass tube, resulting in the current flow.", "fibs": ["flow"]}
{"text": "Thus, light falling on the surface of the emitter causes current in the external circuit.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Hallwachs and Lenard studied how this photo current varied with collector plate potential, and with frequency and intensity of incident light.", "fibs": ["photo"]}
{"text": "Hallwachs, in 1888, undertook the study further and connected a negatively charged zinc plate to an electroscope.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "He observed that the zinc plate lost its charge when it was illuminated by ultraviolet light.", "fibs": ["zinc"]}
{"text": "Further, the uncharged zinc plate became positively charged when it was irradiated by ultraviolet light.", "fibs": ["zinc"]}
{"text": "Positive charge on a  positively charged zinc plate was found to be further enhanced when it was illuminated by ultraviolet light.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "From these observations he concluded that negatively charged particles were emitted from the zinc plate under the action of ultraviolet light.", "fibs": ["zinc"]}
{"text": "After the discovery of the electron in 1897, it became evident that the incident light causes electrons to be emitted from the emitter plate.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "Due to negative charge, the emitted electrons are pushed towards the collector plate by the electric field.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Hallwachs and  Lenard also observed that when ultraviolet light fell on the emitter plate, no electrons were emitted at all when the frequency of the incident light was smaller than a certain minimum value, called the threshold frequency.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "This minimum frequency depends on the nature of the material of the emitter plate.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "It was found that certain metals like zinc, cadmium, magnesium, etc., responded only to ultraviolet light, having short wavelength, to cause electron emission from the surface.", "fibs": ["zinc"]}
{"text": "However, some alkali metals such as lithium, sodium, potassium, caesium and rubidium were sensitive even to visible light.", "fibs": ["lithium"]}
{"text": "All these photosensitive substances emit electrons when they are illuminated by light.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "After the discovery of electrons, these electrons were termed as photoelectrons.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "The phenomenon is called  photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "11.4 Experimental Study of Photoelectric Effect
Figure 11.1 depicts a  schematic view of the arrangement used for the experimental study of the photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "It consists of an evacuated glass/quartz tube having a photosensitive plate C and another metal plate A. Monochromatic light from the source S of sufficiently short wavelength passes through the window W and falls on the photosensitive plate C  (emitter).", "fibs": ["glass/quartz"]}
{"text": "A transparent quartz window is sealed on to the glass tube, which permits ultraviolet radiation to pass through it and irradiate the photosensitive plate C. The electrons are emitted by the plate C and are collected by the plate A (collector), by the electric field created by the battery.", "fibs": ["quartz"]}
{"text": "The battery maintains the potential difference between the plates C and A, that can be varied.", "fibs": ["battery"]}
{"text": "The polarity of the plates C and A can be reversed by a commutator.", "fibs": ["polarity"]}
{"text": "Thus, the plate A can be maintained at a desired positive or negative potential with respect to emitter C. When the collector plate A is positive with respect to the emitter plate C, the electrons are attracted to it.", "fibs": ["plate"]}
{"text": "The emission of electrons causes flow of electric current in the circuit.", "fibs": ["emission"]}
{"text": "The potential difference between the emitter and collector plates is measured by a voltmeter (V) whereas the resulting photo current flowing in the circuit is measured by a microammeter (µA).", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "The photoelectric current can be increased or decreased by varying the potential of collector plate A with respect to the emitter plate C. The intensity and frequency of the incident light can be varied, as can the potential difference V between the emitter C and the collector A.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.1 Experimental arrangement for  study of photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "11.4.1  Effect of intensity of light on photocurrent
The collector A is maintained at a positive potential with respect to emitter C so that electrons ejected from C are attracted towards collector A.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "Keeping the frequency of the incident radiation and the potential fixed, the intensity of light is varied and the resulting photoelectric current is measured each time.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "It is found that the photocurrent increases linearly with intensity of incident light as shown graphically in Fig.", "fibs": ["photocurrent"]}
{"text": "The photocurrent is directly  proportional to the number of photoelectrons emitted per second.", "fibs": ["photocurrent"]}
{"text": "This implies that the number of photoelectrons emitted per second is directly proportional to the intensity of incident radiation.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.2 Variation of Photoelectric current with intensity of light.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "11.4.2  Effect of potential on photoelectric current 
We first keep the plate A at some positive potential with respect to the plate C and illuminate the plate C with light of fixed frequency ν  and fixed intensity I1.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "We next vary the positive potential of plate A gradually and measure the resulting photocurrent each time.", "fibs": ["plate"]}
{"text": "It is found that the photoelectric current increases with increase in positive (accelerating) potential.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "At some stage, for a certain positive potential of plate A, all the emitted electrons are  collected by the plate A and the photoelectric current becomes maximum or  saturates.", "fibs": ["stage"]}
{"text": "If we increase the accelerating potential of plate A further, the photocurrent does not increase.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "This maximum value of the photoelectric current is called  saturation current.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "Saturation current corresponds to the case when all the photoelectrons emitted by the emitter plate C reach the collector plate A.", "fibs": ["Saturation"]}
{"text": "We now apply a negative (retarding) potential to the plate A with respect to the plate C and make it increasingly negative gradually.", "fibs": ["plate"]}
{"text": "When the polarity is reversed, the electrons are repelled and only the most energetic electrons are able to reach the collector A.", "fibs": ["polarity"]}
{"text": "The photocurrent is found to decrease rapidly until it drops to zero at a certain sharply defined, critical value of the negative potential V0 on the plate A.", "fibs": ["photocurrent"]}
{"text": "For a particular frequency of incident radiation, the minimum negative (retarding) potential V0 given to the plate A for which the photocurrent stops or becomes zero is called the cut-off or stopping potential.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.3 Variation of photocurrent with collector plate potential for different intensity of incident radiation.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The interpretation of the observation in terms of photoelectrons is straightforward.", "fibs": ["interpretation"]}
{"text": "All the photoelectrons emitted from the metal do not have the same energy.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "Photoelectric current is zero when the stopping potential is sufficient to repel even the most energetic photoelectrons, with the maximum kinetic energy (Kmax), so that
Kmax = e V0    (11.1)
We can now repeat this experiment with incident radiation of the same frequency but of higher intensity I2 and I3 (I3 > I2 > I1).", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "We note that the saturation currents are now found to be at higher values.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "This shows that more electrons are being emitted per second, proportional to the intensity of incident radiation.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "But the stopping potential remains the same as that for the incident radiation of intensity I1, as shown graphically in Fig.", "fibs": ["incident"]}
{"text": "Thus, for a given frequency of the incident radiation, the stopping potential is independent of its intensity.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "In other words, the maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons depends on the light source and the emitter plate material, but is independent of intensity of incident radiation.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "11.4.3	Effect of frequency of incident radiation on stopping potential
We now study the relation between the frequency ν of the incident radiation and the stopping potential V0.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "We suitably adjust the same intensity of light radiation at various frequencies and study the variation of photocurrent with collector plate potential.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "The resulting variation is shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["variation"]}
{"text": "We obtain different values of stopping potential but the same value of the saturation current for incident radiation of different frequencies.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "The energy of the emitted electrons depends on the frequency of the incident radiations.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The stopping potential is more negative for higher frequencies of incident radiation.", "fibs": ["incident"]}
{"text": "Note from Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "11.4  that the stopping potentials are in the order V03 > V02 > V01 if the frequencies are in the order ν3 > ν2 > ν1 .", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "This implies that greater the frequency of incident light, greater is the maximum kinetic energy of the photoelectrons.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "Consequently, we need greater retarding potential to stop them completely.", "fibs": ["need"]}
{"text": "If we plot a graph between the frequency of incident radiation and the corresponding stopping potential for different metals we get a straight line, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["plot"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.4 Variation of photoelectric current with collector plate potential for different frequencies of incident radiation.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.5 Variation of stopping potential V0 with frequency ν of incident radiation for a given photosensitive material.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The graph shows that
(i)	the stopping potential V0 varies linearly with the frequency of incident radiation for a given photosensitive material.", "fibs": ["graph"]}
{"text": "(ii)	there exists a certain minimum cut-off frequency ν0 for which the stopping potential is zero.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "These observations have two implications:
(i)	The maximum kinetic energy of the photoelectrons varies linearly with the frequency of incident radiation, but is independent of its intensity.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "(ii) For a frequency ν of incident radiation, lower than the cut-off frequency ν0, no photoelectric emission is possible even if the intensity is large.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "This minimum, cut-off frequency ν0, is called the threshold frequency.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "Different photosensitive materials respond differently to light.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Selenium is more sensitive than zinc or copper.", "fibs": ["zinc"]}
{"text": "The same photosensitive substance  gives different response to light of different wavelengths.", "fibs": ["substance"]}
{"text": "For example, ultraviolet light gives rise to  photoelectric effect in copper  while green or red light does not.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Note that in all the above experiments, it is found that, if frequency of the incident radiation exceeds the threshold frequency, the photoelectric emission starts instantaneously without any apparent time lag, even if the incident radiation is very dim.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "It is now known that emission starts in a time of the order of 10–9 s or less.", "fibs": ["emission"]}
{"text": "We now summarise the experimental features and observations described in this section.", "fibs": ["section"]}
{"text": "(i)	For a given photosensitive material and frequency of incident radiation (above the threshold frequency), the photoelectric current is directly proportional to the intensity of incident light (Fig.", "fibs": ["material"]}
{"text": "(ii)	For a given photosensitive material and frequency of incident radiation, saturation current is found to be proportional to the intensity of incident radiation whereas the stopping potential is independent of its intensity (Fig.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii)	For a given photosensitive material, there exists a certain minimum cut-off frequency of the incident radiation, called the threshold frequency, below which no emission of photoelectrons takes place, no matter how intense the incident light is.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "Above the threshold frequency, the stopping potential or equivalently the maximum kinetic energy of the emitted photoelectrons increases linearly with the frequency of the incident radiation, but is independent of its intensity (Fig.", "fibs": ["threshold"]}
{"text": "(iv)	The photoelectric emission is an instantaneous process without any apparent time lag (∼10–9s or less), even when the incident radiation is made exceedingly dim.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "11.5	Photoelectric Effect and Wave Theory oF Light
The wave nature of light was well established by the end of the nineteenth century.", "fibs": ["Effect"]}
{"text": "The phenomena of interference, diffraction and polarisation were explained in a natural and satisfactory way by the wave picture of light.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "According to this picture, light is an electromagnetic wave consisting  of electric and magnetic fields with continuous distribution of energy over the region of space over which the wave is extended.", "fibs": ["picture"]}
{"text": "Let us now see if this wave picture of light can explain the observations on photoelectric  emission given in the previous section.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "According to the wave picture of light, the free electrons at the surface of the metal (over which the beam of radiation falls) absorb the radiant energy continuously.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "The greater the intensity of radiation, the greater are the amplitude of electric and magnetic fields.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Consequently, the greater the intensity, the greater should be the energy absorbed by each electron.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "In this picture, the maximum kinetic energy of the photoelectrons on the surface is then expected to increase with increase in intensity.", "fibs": ["picture"]}
{"text": "Also, no matter what the frequency of radiation is, a sufficiently intense beam of radiation (over sufficient time) should be able to impart enough energy to the electrons, so that they exceed the minimum energy needed to escape from the metal surface .", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "A threshold frequency, therefore, should not exist.", "fibs": ["threshold"]}
{"text": "These expectations of the wave theory directly contradict observations (i), (ii) and (iii) given at the end of sub-section 11.4.3.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Further, we should note that in the wave picture, the absorption of energy by electron takes place continuously over the entire wavefront of the radiation.", "fibs": ["note"]}
{"text": "Since a large number of electrons absorb energy, the energy absorbed per electron per unit time turns out to be small.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Explicit calculations estimate that it can take hours or more for a single electron to pick up sufficient energy to overcome the work function and come out of the metal.", "fibs": ["estimate"]}
{"text": "This conclusion is again in striking contrast to observation (iv) that the photoelectric emission is instantaneous.", "fibs": ["conclusion"]}
{"text": "In short, the wave picture is unable to explain the most basic features of  photoelectric  emission.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "11.6	Einstein’s Photoelectric Equation: Energy Quantum of Radiation
In 1905, Albert Einstein (1879-1955) proposed a radically new picture of electromagnetic radiation to explain photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "In this picture, photoelectric emission does not take place by continuous absorption of energy from radiation.", "fibs": ["picture"]}
{"text": "Radiation energy is built up of discrete units – the so called quanta of energy of radiation.", "fibs": ["Radiation"]}
{"text": "Each quantum of radiant energy has energy hν, where h is Planck’s constant and ν the frequency of light.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "In photoelectric effect, an electron absorbs a quantum of energy (hν) of radiation.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "If this quantum of energy absorbed exceeds the minimum energy needed for the electron to escape from the metal surface (work function φ0), the electron is emitted with maximum kinetic energy 
Kmax = hν – φ0           	(11.2)
More tightly bound electrons will emerge with kinetic energies less than the maximum value.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "Note that the intensity of light of a given frequency is determined by the number of photons incident per second.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Increasing the intensity will increase the number of emitted electrons per second.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "However, the maximum kinetic energy of the emitted photoelectrons is determined by the energy of each photon.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Albert Einstein (1879 – 1955)






Albert Einstein (1879 – 1955) Einstein, one of the greatest physicists of all time, was born in Ulm, Germany.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "In the first paper, he introduced the notion of light quanta (now called photons) and used it to explain the features of photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "In the second paper, he developed a theory of Brownian motion, confirmed experimentally a few years later and provided a convincing evidence of the atomic picture of matter.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "The third paper gave birth to the special theory of relativity.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "In 1916, he published the general theory of relativity.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Some of Einstein’s most significant later contributions are: the notion of stimulated emission introduced in an alternative derivation of Planck’s blackbody radiation law, static model of the universe which started modern cosmology, quantum statistics of a gas of massive bosons, and a critical analysis of the foundations of quantum mechanics.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "In 1921, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in physics for his contribution to theoretical physics and the photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["physics"]}
{"text": "Equation (11.2) is known as Einstein’s photoelectric equation.", "fibs": ["Equation"]}
{"text": "We now see how this equation accounts in a simple and elegant manner all the observations on photoelectric effect given at the end of  sub-section 11.4.3.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "•	According to Eq.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "(11.2), Kmax depends linearly on ν, and is independent of intensity of radiation, in agreement with observation.", "fibs": ["ν"]}
{"text": "This has happened because in Einstein’s picture, photoelectric effect arises from the absorption of a single quantum of radiation by a single electron.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The intensity of radiation (that is proportional to the number of energy quanta per unit area per unit time) is irrelevant to this basic process.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "•	Since Kmax must be non-negative, Eq.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "(11.2 ) implies that photoelectric emission is possible only if
	h ν > φ0
	or 	ν > ν0 , where 
	ν0 =       	(11.3)
 Equation (11.3) shows that the greater the work function φ0, the higher the minimum or threshold frequency ν0 needed to emit photoelectrons.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "Thus, there exists a threshold frequency ν0 (= φ0/h) for the metal surface, below which no photoelectric  emission is possible, no matter how intense the incident radiation may be or how long it falls on the surface.", "fibs": ["threshold"]}
{"text": "•	In this picture, intensity of radiation as noted above, is proportional to the number of energy quanta per unit area per unit time.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "The greater the number of energy quanta available, the greater is the number of electrons absorbing the energy quanta  and greater, therefore, is the number of electrons coming out of the metal (for ν > ν0).", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "This explains why, for ν > ν0 , photoelectric current is proportional to intensity.", "fibs": ["ν"]}
{"text": "•	In Einstein’s picture, the basic elementary process involved in photoelectric effect is the absorption of a light quantum by an electron.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "This process is instantaneous.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Thus, whatever may be the intensity i.e., the number of quanta of radiation per unit area per unit time, photoelectric emission is instantaneous.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Low intensity does not mean delay in emission, since the basic elementary process is the same.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Intensity only determines how many electrons are able to participate in the elementary process (absorption of a light quantum by a single electron) and, therefore, the photoelectric current.", "fibs": ["Intensity"]}
{"text": "Using Eq.", "fibs": ["Eq."]}
{"text": "(11.1), the photoelectric equation, Eq.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "(11.2), can be written as
e V0 = h ν  – φ0; for 
or  V0 =  (11.4) 
This is an important result.", "fibs": ["h"]}
{"text": "It predicts that the V0 versus ν  curve is a straight line with slope = (h/e), independent of the nature of the material.", "fibs": ["ν"]}
{"text": "During 1906-1916, Millikan performed a series of experiments on photoelectric effect, aimed at disproving Einstein’s photoelectric equation.", "fibs": ["series"]}
{"text": "He measured the slope of the straight line obtained for sodium, similar to that shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["slope"]}
{"text": "Using the known value of e, he determined the value of Planck’s constant h. This value was close to the value of Planck’s contant (= 6.626 × 10–34J s) determined in an entirely different context.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "In this way, in 1916, Millikan proved the validity of Einstein’s photoelectric equation, instead of disproving it.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "The successful explanation of photoelectric effect using the hypothesis of light quanta and the experimental determination of values of h and φ0, in agreement with values obtained from other experiments, led to the acceptance of Einstein’s picture of photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["explanation"]}
{"text": "Millikan verified photoelectric equation with great precision, for a number of alkali metals over a wide range of radiation frequencies.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "11.7  Particle Nature of Light: The Photon
Photoelectric effect thus gave evidence to the strange fact that light in interaction with matter behaved as if it was made of quanta or packets of energy, each of energy h ν.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "Is the light quantum of energy to be associated with a particle?", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Einstein arrived at the important result, that the light quantum can also be associated with momentum (h ν/c).", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "A definite value of energy as well as momentum is a strong sign that the light quantum can be associated with a particle.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "This particle was later named photon.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "The particle-like behaviour of light was further confirmed, in 1924, by the experiment of A.H. Compton (1892-1962) on scattering of X-rays from electrons.", "fibs": ["behaviour"]}
{"text": "In 1921, Einstein was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for his contribution to theoretical physics and the photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["contribution"]}
{"text": "In 1923, Millikan was awarded the Nobel Prize in physics for his work on the elementary charge of electricity and on the photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["physics"]}
{"text": "We can summarise the photon picture of electromagnetic  radiation as follows:
(i) In interaction of radiation with matter, radiation behaves as if it is made up of particles called photons.", "fibs": ["photon"]}
{"text": "(ii) Each photon has energy E (=hν) and momentum p (= h ν/c), and  speed c, the speed of light.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "(iii)	All photons of light of a particular frequency  ν, or wavelength λ, have the same energy E (=hν = hc/λ) and momentum  p (= hν/c= h/λ), whatever the intensity of radiation may be.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "By increasing the intensity of light of given wavelength, there is only an increase in the number of photons per second crossing a given area, with each photon having the same energy.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Thus, photon energy is independent of intensity of radiation.", "fibs": ["photon"]}
{"text": "(iv) Photons are electrically neutral and are not deflected by electric and magnetic fields.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "(v) In a photon-particle collision (such as photon-electron collision), the total energy and total momentum are conserved.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "However, the number of photons may not be conserved in a collision.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The photon may be absorbed or a new photon may be created.", "fibs": ["photon"]}
