{"text": "11.8  Wave Nature of Matter
The dual (wave-particle) nature of light (electromagnetic radiation, in general) comes out clearly from what we have learnt in this and the preceding chapters.", "fibs": ["Matter"]}
{"text": "The wave nature of light shows up in the phenomena of interference, diffraction and polarisation.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, in photoelectric effect and Compton effect which involve energy and momentum transfer, radiation behaves as if it is made up of a bunch of particles – the photons.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "Whether a particle or wave description is best suited for understanding an experiment depends on the nature of the experiment.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "For example, in the familiar  phenomenon of seeing an object by our eye, both descriptions are important.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The gathering and focussing mechanism of light by the eye-lens is well described in the wave picture.", "fibs": ["gathering"]}
{"text": "But its absorption by the rods and cones (of the retina) requires the photon picture of light.", "fibs": ["absorption"]}
{"text": "A natural question arises: If radiation has a dual (wave-particle) nature, might not the particles of nature (the electrons, protons, etc.)", "fibs": ["question"]}
{"text": "also exhibit wave-like character?", "fibs": ["exhibit"]}
{"text": "In 1924, the French physicist Louis Victor de Broglie (pronounced as de Broy) (1892-1987) put forward the bold hypothesis that moving particles of matter should display wave-like properties under suitable conditions.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "He reasoned that nature was symmetrical and that the two basic physical entities – matter and energy, must have symmetrical character.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "If radiation shows dual aspects, so should matter.", "fibs": ["radiation"]}
{"text": "De Broglie proposed that the wave length λ  associated with a particle of momentum p is given as
