A photocell is a technological application of the photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "It is a device whose electrical properties are affected by light.", "fibs": ["device"]}
{"text": "It is also sometimes called an electric eye.", "fibs": ["eye"]}
{"text": "A photocell consists of a semi-cylindrical photo-sensitive metal plate C (emitter) and a wire loop A (collector) supported in an evacuated glass or quartz bulb.", "fibs": ["photocell"]}
{"text": "It is connected to the external circuit having a high-tension battery B and microammeter (µA) as shown in the Figure.", "fibs": ["circuit"]}
{"text": "Sometimes, instead of the plate C, a thin layer of photosensitive material is pasted on the inside of the bulb.", "fibs": ["plate"]}
{"text": "A part of the bulb is left clean for the light to enter it.", "fibs": ["part"]}
{"text": "A photo cell
When light of suitable wavelength falls on the emitter C, photoelectrons are emitted.", "fibs": ["photo"]}
{"text": "These photoelectrons are drawn to the collector A. Photocurrent of the order of a few microampere can be normally obtained from a photo cell.", "fibs": ["collector"]}
{"text": "A photocell converts a change in intensity of illumination into a change in photocurrent.", "fibs": ["photocell"]}
{"text": "This current can be used to operate control systems and in light measuring devices.", "fibs": ["control"]}
{"text": "A photocell of lead sulphide sensitive to infrared radiation is used in electronic ignition circuits.", "fibs": ["photocell"]}
{"text": "A Photo cell
In scientific work, photo cells are used whenever it is necessary to measure the intensity of light.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Light meters in photographic cameras make use of photo cells to measure the intensity of incident light.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "The photocells, inserted in the door light electric circuit, are used as automatic door opener.", "fibs": ["door"]}
{"text": "A person approaching a doorway may interrupt a light beam which is incident on a photocell.", "fibs": ["person"]}
{"text": "The abrupt change in photocurrent may be used to start a motor which opens the door or rings an alarm.", "fibs": ["change"]}
{"text": "They are used in the control of a counting device which records every interruption of the light beam caused by a person or object passing across the beam.", "fibs": ["control"]}
{"text": "So photocells help count the persons entering an auditorium, provided they enter the hall one by one.", "fibs": ["count"]}
{"text": "They are used for detection of traffic law defaulters: an alarm may be sounded whenever a beam of (invisible) radiation is intercepted.", "fibs": ["detection"]}
{"text": "In burglar alarm, (invisible) ultraviolet light is continuously made to fall on a photocell installed at the doorway.", "fibs": ["burglar"]}
{"text": "A person entering the door interrupts the beam falling on the photocell.", "fibs": ["person"]}
{"text": "The abrupt change in photocurrent is used to start an electric bell ringing.", "fibs": ["change"]}
{"text": "In fire alarm, a number of photocells are installed at suitable places in a building.", "fibs": ["fire"]}
{"text": "In the event of breaking out of fire, light radiations fall upon the photocell.", "fibs": ["event"]}
{"text": "This completes the electric circuit through an electric bell or a siren which starts operating as a warning signal.", "fibs": ["circuit"]}
{"text": "Photocells are used in the reproduction of sound in motion pictures and in the television camera for scanning and telecasting scenes.", "fibs": ["reproduction"]}
{"text": "They are used in industries for detecting minor flaws or holes in metal sheets.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
