{"text": "We describe the experimental verification of the de Broglie hypothesis in the next section.", "fibs": ["verification"]}
{"text": "In 1929, de Broglie was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for his discovery of the wave nature of electrons.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "Louis Victor de Broglie (1892 – 1987)





Louis Victor de Broglie (1892 – 1987) French physicist who put forth revolutionary idea of wave nature of matter.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "This idea was developed by Erwin Schródinger into a full-fledged theory of quantum mechanics commonly known as wave mechanics.", "fibs": ["idea"]}
{"text": "In 1929, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for his discovery of the wave nature of electrons.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "The matter–wave picture elegantly incorporated the Heisenberg’s uncertainty principle.", "fibs": ["matter–wave"]}
{"text": "According to the principle, it is not possible to measure both the position and momentum of an electron (or any other particle) at the same time exactly.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "There is always some uncertainty (∆ x) in the specification of position and some uncertainty (∆p) in the specification of momentum.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "The product of  ∆x and ∆p is of the order of ö* (with ö = h/2π), i.e.,
∆x ∆p ≈ ö	(11.12) 
Equation (11.12) allows the possibility that ∆x is zero; but then ∆p must be infinite in order that the product is non-zero.", "fibs": ["product"]}
{"text": "Similarly, if ∆p is zero, ∆x must be infinite.", "fibs": ["∆p"]}
{"text": "Ordinarily, both ∆x and ∆p are non-zero such that their product is of the order of ö.", "fibs": ["∆x"]}
{"text": "Now, if an electron has a definite momentum p, (i.e.∆p = 0), by the de Broglie relation, it has a definite wavelength λ.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "A wave of definite (single) wavelength extends all over space.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "By Born’s probability interpretation this means that the electron is not localised in any finite region of space.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "That is, its position uncertainty is infinite (∆x → ∞), which is consistent with the uncertainty principle.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "* A more rigorous treatment gives ∆x ∆p ≥  ö /2.", "fibs": ["treatment"]}
{"text": "In general, the matter wave associated with the electron is not extended all over space.", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "It is a wave packet extending over some finite region of space.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "In that case ∆x is not infinite but has some finite value depending on the extension of the wave packet.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Also, you must appreciate that a wave packet of finite extension does not have a single wavelength.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "It is built up of wavelengths spread around some central wavelength.", "fibs": ["spread"]}
{"text": "By de Broglie’s relation, then, the momentum of the electron will also have a spread – an uncertainty ∆p.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "This is as expected from the uncertainty principle.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "It can be shown that the wave packet description together with de Broglie relation and Born’s probability interpretation reproduce the Heisenberg’s uncertainty principle exactly.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.6 (a) The wave packet description of an electron.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The wave packet corresponds to a spread of wavelength around some central wavelength (and hence by de Broglie relation,  a spread in momentum).", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Consequently, it is associated with an uncertainty in position  (∆x) and an uncertainty in momentum (∆p).", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "(b) The matter wave corresponding to a  definite momentum of an electron  extends all over space.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "In this case,  ∆p = 0 and ∆ x → ∞.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "In Chapter 12, the de Broglie relation will be seen to justify Bohr’s postulate on quantisation of angular momentum of electron in an atom.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.6 shows a schematic diagram of (a) a localised wave packet, and (b) an extended wave with fixed wavelength.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
