{"text": "Probability interpretation to matter waves

It is worth pausing here to reflect on just what a matter wave associated with a particle, say, an electron, means.", "fibs": ["Probability"]}
{"text": "Actually, a truly satisfactory physical understanding of the dual nature of matter and radiation has not emerged so far.", "fibs": ["understanding"]}
{"text": "The great founders of quantum mechanics (Niels Bohr, Albert Einstein, and many others) struggled with this and related concepts for long.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "Still the deep physical interpretation of quantum mechanics continues to be an area of active research.", "fibs": ["interpretation"]}
{"text": "Despite this, the concept of matter wave has been mathematically introduced in modern quantum mechanics with great success.", "fibs": ["concept"]}
{"text": "An important milestone in this connection was when Max Born (1882-1970) suggested a probability interpretation to the matter wave amplitude.", "fibs": ["milestone"]}
{"text": "According to this, the intensity (square of the amplitude) of the matter wave at a point determines the probability density of the particle at that point.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Probability density means probability per unit volume.", "fibs": ["Probability"]}
{"text": "Thus, if A is the amplitude of the wave at a point, |A|2 ∆V is the probability of the particle being found in a small volume ∆V around that point.", "fibs": ["amplitude"]}
{"text": "Thus, if the intensity of matter wave is large in a certain region, there is a greater probability of the particle being found there than where the intensity is small.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
