{"text": "11.9  Davisson and Germer Experiment
The wave nature of electrons was first experimentally verified by C.J.", "fibs": ["Experiment"]}
{"text": "Thomson, in 1928, who observed diffraction effects with beams of electrons scattered by crystals.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "Davisson and Thomson shared the Nobel Prize in 1937 for their experimental discovery of diffraction of electrons by crystals.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "The experimental arrange-ment used by Davisson and Germer is schematically shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "It consists of an electron gun which comprises of a tungsten filament F, coated with barium oxide and heated by a low voltage power supply (L.T.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "or battery).", "fibs": ["battery"]}
{"text": "Electrons emitted by the filament are accelerated to a desired velocity by applying suitable potential/voltage from a high voltage power supply (H.T.", "fibs": ["filament"]}
{"text": "or battery).", "fibs": ["battery"]}
{"text": "They are made to pass through a cylinder with fine holes along its axis, producing a fine collimated beam.", "fibs": ["cylinder"]}
{"text": "The beam is made to fall on the surface of a nickel crystal.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "The electrons are scattered in all directions by the atoms of the crystal.", "fibs": ["crystal"]}
{"text": "The intensity of the electron beam, scattered in a given direction, is measured by the electron detector (collector).", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "The detector can be moved on a circular scale and is connected to a sensitive galvanometer, which records the current.", "fibs": ["detector"]}
{"text": "The deflection of the galvanometer is proportional to the intensity of the electron beam entering the collector.", "fibs": ["deflection"]}
{"text": "The  apparatus is enclosed in an evacuated chamber.", "fibs": ["apparatus"]}
{"text": "By moving the  detector  on the circular scale at different positions, the intensity of the scattered electron beam is measured for different values of angle of scattering θ which is the angle between the incident and the scattered electron beams.", "fibs": ["detector"]}
{"text": "The variation of the intensity (I) of the scattered electrons with the angle of scattering θ  is obtained for different accelerating voltages.", "fibs": ["variation"]}
{"text": "Figure 11.7 Davisson-Germer electron diffraction arrangement.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The experiment was performed by varying the accelarating voltage from 44 V to 68 V. It was noticed that a strong peak appeared in the intensity (I) of the scattered electron for an accelarating voltage of 54V at a scattering angle θ = 50°
The appearance of the peak in a particular direction is due to the constructive interference of electrons scattered from different layers of the regularly spaced atoms of the crystals.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "From the electron diffraction measurements, the wavelength of matter waves was found to be 0.165 nm.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "The de Broglie wavelength λ associated with electrons, using Eq.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "(11.11), for V = 54 V is given by
λ = h /p  nm
λ  nm =  0.167 nm
Thus, there is an excellent agreement between the theoretical value and the experimentally obtained value of de Broglie wavelength.", "fibs": ["V"]}
{"text": "Davisson-Germer experiment thus strikingly confirms the wave nature of electrons and the de Broglie relation.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "More recently, in 1989, the wave nature of a beam of electrons was experimentally demonstrated in a double-slit experiment, similar to that used for the wave nature of light.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Also, in an experiment in 1994, interference fringes were obtained with the beams of iodine molecules, which are about a million times more massive than electrons.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "The de Broglie hypothesis has been basic to the development of modern quantum mechanics.", "fibs": ["hypothesis"]}
{"text": "It has also led to the field of electron optics.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The wave properties of electrons have been utilised in the design of electron microscope which is a great improvement, with higher resolution, over the optical microscope.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "The minimum energy needed by an electron to come out from a  metal surface is called the work function of the metal.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Energy (greater than the work function (φο) required for electron emission from the metal surface can be supplied by suitably heating or applying strong electric field or irradiating it by light of suitable frequency.", "fibs": ["work"]}
{"text": "Photoelectric effect is the phenomenon of emission of electrons by metals when illuminated by light of suitable frequency.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "Certain metals respond to ultraviolet light while others are sensitive even to the visible light.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Photoelectric effect involves conversion of light energy into electrical energy.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "It follows the law of conservation of energy.", "fibs": ["law"]}
{"text": "The photoelectric emission is an instantaneous process and possesses certain special features.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "Photoelectric current depends on (i) the intensity of incident light, (ii) the potential difference applied between the two electrodes, and (iii) the nature of the emitter material.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "The stopping potential (Vo) depends on (i) the frequency of incident light, and (ii) the nature of the emitter material.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "For a given frequency of incident light, it is independent of its intensity.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "The stopping potential is directly related to the maximum kinetic energy of electrons emitted: e V0 = (1/2) m v2max = Kmax.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Below a certain frequency (threshold frequency) ν0, characteristic of the metal, no photoelectric emission takes place, no matter how large the intensity may be.", "fibs": ["frequency"]}
{"text": "The classical wave theory could not explain the main features of photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Its picture of continuous absorption of energy from radiation could not explain the independence of Kmax on intensity, the existence of νo and the instantaneous nature of the process.", "fibs": ["picture"]}
{"text": "Einstein explained these features on the basis of photon picture of light.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "According to this, light is composed of discrete packets of energy called quanta or photons.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Each photon carries an energy E (= h ν) and momentum p (= h/λ), which depend on the frequency (ν ) of incident light and not on its intensity.", "fibs": ["photon"]}
{"text": "Photoelectric emission from the metal surface occurs due to absorption of a photon by an electron.", "fibs": ["emission"]}
{"text": "Einstein’s photoelectric equation is in accordance with the energy conservation law as applied to the photon absorption by an electron in the metal.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The maximum kinetic energy (1/2)m v2max is equal to the photon energy (hν) minus the work function φ0 (= hν0) of the target metal: 
 m v2max = V0 e = hν – φ0 = h (ν – ν0) 
 This photoelectric equation explains all the features of the photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Millikan’s first precise measurements confirmed the Einstein’s photoelectric equation and obtained an accurate value of Planck’s constant h. This led to the acceptance of particle or photon description (nature) of electromagnetic radiation, introduced by Einstein.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Radiation has dual nature: wave and particle.", "fibs": ["Radiation"]}
{"text": "The nature of experiment determines whether a wave or particle description is best suited for understanding the experimental result.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "Reasoning that radiation and matter should be symmetrical in nature, Louis Victor de Broglie attributed a wave-like character to matter (material particles).", "fibs": ["Reasoning"]}
{"text": "The waves associated with the moving material particles are called matter waves or de Broglie waves.", "fibs": ["material"]}
{"text": "The de Broglie wavelength (λ) associated with a moving particle is related to its momentum p as:  λ = h/p.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "The dualism of matter is inherent in the de Broglie relation which contains a wave concept (λ) and a particle concept (p).", "fibs": ["dualism"]}
{"text": "The de Broglie wavelength is independent of the charge and nature of the material  particle.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "It is significantly measurable (of the order of the atomic-planes spacing in crystals) only in case of sub-atomic particles like electrons, protons, etc.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "(due to smallness of their masses and hence, momenta).", "fibs": ["smallness"]}
{"text": "However, it is indeed very small, quite beyond measurement, in case of macroscopic objects, commonly  encountered in everyday life.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "Electron diffraction experiments by Davisson and Germer, and by G. P. Thomson, as well as many later experiments, have verified and confirmed the wave-nature of electrons.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "The de Broglie hypothesis of matter waves supports the Bohr’s concept of stationary orbits.", "fibs": ["hypothesis"]}
{"text": "Free electrons in a metal are free in the sense that they move inside the metal in a constant potential (This is only an approximation).", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "They are not free to move out of the metal.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "They need additional energy to get out of the metal.", "fibs": ["need"]}
{"text": "Free electrons in a metal do not all have the same energy.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "Like molecules in a gas jar, the electrons have a certain energy distribution at a given temperature.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "This distribution is different from the usual Maxwell’s distribution that you have learnt in the study of kinetic theory of gases.", "fibs": ["distribution"]}
{"text": "You will learn about it in later courses, but the difference has to do with the fact that electrons obey Pauli’s exclusion principle.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "Because of the energy distribution of free electrons in a metal, the energy required by an electron to come out of the metal is different for different electrons.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Electrons with higher energy require less additional energy to come out of the metal than those with lower energies.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Work function is the least energy required by an electron to come out of the metal.", "fibs": ["Work"]}
{"text": "Observations on photoelectric effect imply that in the event of matter-light interaction, absorption of energy takes place in discrete units of hν.", "fibs": ["photoelectric"]}
{"text": "This is not quite the same as saying that light consists of particles, each of energy hν.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Observations on the stopping potential (its independence of intensity and dependence on frequency) are the crucial discriminator between the wave-picture and photon-picture of photoelectric effect.", "fibs": ["independence"]}
{"text": "The wavelength of a matter wave given by   has physical significance; its phase velocity  vp has no physical significance.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "However, the group velocity of the matter wave is physically meaningful and equals the velocity of the particle.", "fibs": ["group"]}
